  "opinion": "As a school teacher in Los Angeles with a background that reflects the diverse educational experiences many of my students come from, I’ve seen firsthand how stereotype threat can quietly undermine potential in STEM fields. Stereotype threat occurs when individuals internalize negative stereotypes about their group’s abilities, leading to anxiety that hinders performance. For example, a girl in my classroom who’s always excelling in math might suddenly become hesitant during a group project because she worries her peers will assume she’s not ‘good at science’—a belief that’s often reinforced by societal messages. This isn’t just theoretical; it’s real for students who grow up seeing limited role models in STEM, especially girls from under-resourced communities or those whose families didn’t emphasize academic rigor. We absolutely must address this issue. In my classroom, I’ve started by normalizing conversations about bias and creating safe spaces where students can share their fears without judgment. I also partner with local universities to bring in diverse role models—scientists, engineers, and mathematicians from backgrounds similar to my students—to show that success in STEM is attainable for everyone. The key isn’t just awareness but actionable change: curriculum adjustments that highlight diverse contributions to science, mentorship programs that build confidence, and teacher training that equips educators to spot and counteract stereotypes. It’s a slow process, but one that’s essential for ensuring all students, regardless of their background, feel empowered to pursue their passions in STEM. My own experience as a teacher has taught me that empathy and proactive support can dismantle barriers more effectively than any policy alone.",
